INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`, `title`, `summary`, `tags`, `banner_image_path`, `directions_md`, `directions_html`, `content_md`, `content_html`, `pubDate`, `url`) VALUES
(1, 'Chicken Katsu Curry', 'Wagamama inspired Katsu Curry', 'Japanese chicken curry', 'chicken-katsu-curry.jpg', '1.   Blend 2 tbsp sunflower oil, 2 onions, 5 garlic cloves, 2 carrots, 2 tbsp plain flour, 4 tsp curry powder, 600ml chicken stock, 2 tsp honey, 4 tsp soy sauce, 1 bay leaf, and 1 tsp garam masala to make the curry sauce.\r\n2.   Heat for 10-12 minutes over a low heat.\r\n3.   Simmer for 20 minutes until it thickens.\r\n4.   For the chicken, season with salt and pepper, coat in flour, then a beaten egg, and finally in Panko breadcrumbs all over.\r\n5.   Shallow fry for 10 minutes.', '<ol>\n<li>Blend 2 tbsp sunflower oil, 2 onions, 5 garlic cloves, 2 carrots, 2 tbsp plain flour, 4 tsp curry powder, 600ml chicken stock, 2 tsp honey, 4 tsp soy sauce, 1 bay leaf, and 1 tsp garam masala to make the curry sauce.</li>\n<li>Heat for 10-12 minutes over a low heat.</li>\n<li>Simmer for 20 minutes until it thickens.</li>\n<li>For the chicken, season with salt and pepper, coat in flour, then a beaten egg, and finally in Panko breadcrumbs all over.</li>\n<li>Shallow fry for 10 minutes.</li>\n</ol>\n', 'We found the recipe relatively straightforward and easy to follow. We think you could even blitz the veg instead of sieving it to minimise waste. To get that iconic Wagamama rice dome, pack the rice into a suitably sized bowl that has been lightly coated with oil. Place a plate on top of it, then turn it all over so the bowl is now upside-down, then remove the bowl slowly (you may have to give it a slight tap).\r\n\r\nOverall the meal was delicious however the chicken can be a little greasy. It is definitely worth padding it with kitchen paper to absorb any excess. Having tried the original Wagamama recipe, this is an extremely close recipe. Enjoy!\r\n\r\n[![chicken katsu curry](img/chicken-katsu-curry.jpg "Just like Wagamama")](img/chicken-katsu-curry.jpg)\r\n<p class="caption" markdown="1">So easy, and fast!</p>', '<p>We found the recipe relatively straightforward and easy to follow. We think you could even blitz the veg instead of sieving it to minimise waste. To get that iconic Wagamama rice dome, pack the rice into a suitably sized bowl that has been lightly coated with oil. Place a plate on top of it, then turn it all over so the bowl is now upside-down, then remove the bowl slowly (you may have to give it a slight tap).</p>\n\n<p>Overall the meal was delicious however the chicken can be a little greasy. It is definitely worth padding it with kitchen paper to absorb any excess. Having tried the original Wagamama recipe, this is an extremely close recipe. Enjoy!</p>\n\n<a href="img/chicken-katsu-curry.jpg"><img src="img/chicken-katsu-curry.jpg" alt="chicken katsu curry" title="Just like Wagamama" /></a>\n\n<p class="caption">So easy, and fast!</p>\n', '2015-01-18 12:01:53', 'chicken-katsu-curry'),
(2, 'Three Sauce Chicken Thighs', 'Chicken thighs marinated in three different chilli sauces', 'chicken chilli sauce gochujang', '3-sauce-wings.jpg', '1. Mix salt and pepper in the flour and coat the thighs thoroughly.\r\n2. Place in the oven for 20 mins.\r\n3. Blend the gochujang, shallots, soy, garlic, ginger, and rice wine vinegar for the gochujan sauce.\r\n4. Heat some Frank''s hot sauce in a pan and add the honey for the second sauce.\r\n5. Place some BBQ sauce in a bowl for the third sauce.\r\n6. When the chicken is sizzling and brown, coat the thighs with the three sauces using a basting brush.\r\n7. Add back to the oven for 10-12 mins to crisp up.', '<ol>\n<li>Mix salt and pepper in the flour and coat the thighs thoroughly.</li>\n<li>Place in the oven for 20 mins.</li>\n<li>Blend the gochujang, shallots, soy, garlic, ginger, and rice wine vinegar for the gochujan sauce.</li>\n<li>Heat some Frank''s hot sauce in a pan and add the honey for the second sauce.</li>\n<li>Place some BBQ sauce in a bowl for the third sauce.</li>\n<li>When the chicken is sizzling and brown, coat the thighs with the three sauces using a basting brush.</li>\n<li>Add back to the oven for 10-12 mins to crisp up.</li>\n</ol>\n', 'This is an ideal recipe for the post Christmas lull when you need to use up some left over meat. The chilli sauces will also banish those winter blues by providing some much needed heat!\r\n\r\n#### Sauce one - Gochujang\r\n[Gochujang](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gochujang "Gochujang Wikipedia article") is a Korean red chilli paste, it adds a nice kick to any marinade without being too hot. Although not particularly common here in the UK, it can be found in specialist food outlets, or [online](http://www.amazon.co.uk/Daesang-Sunchang-Gochujang-Pepper-500g/dp/B002WTE0MQ "Buy Gochujang at Amazon") (we got ours from a local Chinese supermarket). The taste of Gochujang is very strong, so the other ingredients were added to try and temper the mix.\r\n\r\n#### Sauce two - Hot Toddy\r\nThis sauce takes a popular wing sauce and makes it seasonal by adding some honey. This gives it a nice medicinal feeling which hits the spot at this time of year.\r\n\r\n#### Sauce three - BBQ\r\nWe were that hungry by now that for the third sauce we just used a bottle of readily available BBQ sauce!\r\n\r\nJust letting the chicken catch slightly gave the marinades a nice charred taste which added to the flavour. Using thighs with the skin on also added to an overall better taste.', '<p>This is an ideal recipe for the post Christmas lull when you need to use up some left over meat. The chilli sauces will also banish those winter blues by providing some much needed heat!</p>\n\n<h4>Sauce one - Gochujang</h4>\n\n<p><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gochujang" title="Gochujang Wikipedia article">Gochujang</a> is a Korean red chilli paste, it adds a nice kick to any marinade without being too hot. Although not particularly common here in the UK, it can be found in specialist food outlets, or <a href="http://www.amazon.co.uk/Daesang-Sunchang-Gochujang-Pepper-500g/dp/B002WTE0MQ" title="Buy Gochujang at Amazon">online</a> (we got ours from a local Chinese supermarket). The taste of Gochujang is very strong, so the other ingredients were added to try and temper the mix.</p>\n\n<h4>Sauce two - Hot Toddy</h4>\n\n<p>This sauce takes a popular wing sauce and makes it seasonal by adding some honey. This gives it a nice medicinal feeling which hits the spot at this time of year.</p>\n\n<h4>Sauce three - BBQ</h4>\n\n<p>We were that hungry by now that for the third sauce we just used a bottle of readily available BBQ sauce!</p>\n\n<p>Just letting the chicken catch slightly gave the marinades a nice charred taste which added to the flavour. Using thighs with the skin on also added to an overall better taste.</p>\n', '2015-01-18 17:56:01', 'three-sauce-chicken-thighs'),
(7, 'Creme Fraiche Pasta', 'A creamy pasta sauce with creme fraiche', 'pasta creme-fraiche', 'creme-fraiche-pasta.jpg', '1.   Fry off some pancetta with oil and garlic.\r\n2.   Add chopped leeks and soften.\r\n3.   Add sliced mushrooms.\r\n4.   Cover with creme fraiche and stir.\r\n5.   Add frozen peas.\r\n6.   Add chopped mint and juice of half a lemon.\r\n7.   Stir in pasta.', '<ol>\n<li>Fry off some pancetta with oil and garlic.</li>\n<li>Add chopped leeks and soften.</li>\n<li>Add sliced mushrooms.</li>\n<li>Cover with creme fraiche and stir.</li>\n<li>Add frozen peas.</li>\n<li>Add chopped mint and juice of half a lemon.</li>\n<li>Stir in pasta.</li>\n</ol>\n', 'This is a useful recipe to use up left over veg. In addition to leeks you can use carrots or peppers.\r\n\r\nIt is extremely quick too. Once the pasta has boiled and the pancetta has browned, you''re on the home straight.\r\n\r\nTop with a few basil leaves and parmesan for an authentic kick.\r\n\r\nIf you want to convert it to be a more healthier alternative, swap the creme fraiche for greek yoghurt.', '<p>This is a useful recipe to use up left over veg. In addition to leeks you can use carrots or peppers.</p>\n\n<p>It is extremely quick too. Once the pasta has boiled and the pancetta has browned, you''re on the home straight.</p>\n\n<p>Top with a few basil leaves and parmesan for an authentic kick.</p>\n\n<p>If you want to convert it to be a more healthier alternative, swap the creme fraiche for greek yoghurt.</p>\n', '2015-03-07 17:02:59', 'creme-fraiche-pasta'),
(8, 'Bulgogi Beef Sandwich', 'A Korean American mash up', 'beef gochujang cheesesteak sandwich', 'placeholder.jpg', '1.   Season beef and place in oven at mark 5 for 40 minutes.\r\n2.   Blend 2 tbsp of Gochujang with 2 tbsp of soy, 1 tbsp rice wine vinegar, and 2 cloves of garlic.\r\n3.   Fry off a couple of peppers, carrots and onions.\r\n4.   Place sub or baguette in oven.\r\n5.   Shred beef and mix into sauce.\r\n6.   Fill subs, lay over some Emmenthal cheese and place back in oven until it has melted.', '<ol>\n<li>Season beef and place in oven at mark 5 for 40 minutes.</li>\n<li>Blend 2 tbsp of Gochujang with 2 tbsp of soy, 1 tbsp rice wine vinegar, and 2 cloves of garlic.</li>\n<li>Fry off a couple of peppers, carrots and onions.</li>\n<li>Place sub or baguette in oven.</li>\n<li>Shred beef and mix into sauce.</li>\n<li>Fill subs, lay over some Emmenthal cheese and place back in oven until it has melted.</li>\n</ol>\n', 'There are few things in life more satisfying to a hungry man than a good sandwich. Imagine then, the solemn joy that is induced when that hungry man stumbles across a ''worldy'' of a sandwich like the filthy Bulgogi pulled beef beast.\r\n\r\n<p class="peter">I concur. This is how I imagine a fusion of Korean and American street vendor food to look. The Philly cheese-steak sandwich slapped right in the face with explosive Korean flavour.</p>\r\n\r\nIt''s shaped like a torpedo and the flavour it packs is just as powerful. Like all good sandwich fillings it''s simple. Slow cooked pulled beef that is then mixed with a sauce that deserves statues in its honour. The main ingredient to the sauce is Gochujang, which is then added to with soy sauce, rice wine vinegar, and a little seasoning. The resulting sauce is infinitely more remarkable than the sum of its parts. A wonderful punch of fruity flavour that borders on the obscene is laced with a well-meaning kick of spice. Reliving the flavour in my minds-mouth is making me question whether I''ve stumbled across a food that transcends this 4 dimensional world of ours and gives its consumer a brief insight to the 5th dimension. If there''s ever a Nobel prize for sarnies, the inventor of Bulgogi surely gets my vote.\r\n\r\nA fresh baked sub roll that''s still warm when filled to bursting with the beef and topped with Emmenthal and grilled immediately before serving....BOOM!\r\n\r\n![bulgogi beef sandwich](img/Bulgogi-Cheesesteak-Sandwich.jpg "Bulgogi Beef Sandwich")\r\n<p class="caption" markdown="1">Let the bulgogi sauce soak into the bread for extra flavour.</p>\r\n\r\n*[''worldy'']: Other-worldly, ethereal, outstanding.', '<p>There are few things in life more satisfying to a hungry man than a good sandwich. Imagine then, the solemn joy that is induced when that hungry man stumbles across a <abbr title="Other-worldly, ethereal, outstanding.">''worldy''</abbr> of a sandwich like the filthy Bulgogi pulled beef beast.</p>\n\n<p class="peter">I concur. This is how I imagine a fusion of Korean and American street vendor food to look. The Philly cheese-steak sandwich slapped right in the face with explosive Korean flavour.</p>\n\n<p>It''s shaped like a torpedo and the flavour it packs is just as powerful. Like all good sandwich fillings it''s simple. Slow cooked pulled beef that is then mixed with a sauce that deserves statues in its honour. The main ingredient to the sauce is Gochujang, which is then added to with soy sauce, rice wine vinegar, and a little seasoning. The resulting sauce is infinitely more remarkable than the sum of its parts. A wonderful punch of fruity flavour that borders on the obscene is laced with a well-meaning kick of spice. Reliving the flavour in my minds-mouth is making me question whether I''ve stumbled across a food that transcends this 4 dimensional world of ours and gives its consumer a brief insight to the 5th dimension. If there''s ever a Nobel prize for sarnies, the inventor of Bulgogi surely gets my vote.</p>\n\n<p>A fresh baked sub roll that''s still warm when filled to bursting with the beef and topped with Emmenthal and grilled immediately before serving....BOOM!</p>\n\n<img src="img/Bulgogi-Cheesesteak-Sandwich.jpg" alt="bulgogi beef sandwich" title="Bulgogi Beef Sandwich" />\n\n<p class="caption">Let the bulgogi sauce soak into the bread for extra flavour.</p>\n', '2015-03-13 11:35:55', 'bulgogi-beef-sandwich'),
(11, 'Pizza al forno', 'A quick, authentic Italian pizza', 'Italian pizza', 'pizza-al-forno-zoomed.jpg', '1.   For the base, mix 240g of flour with a little salt and small amounts of water until it binds.\r\n2.   For the sauce, blend a tin of chopped tomatoes with a handful of basil, 2 garlic cloves, a lug of olive oil and a splash of balsamic.\r\n3.   Roll the base and place it in a pan with a lug of oil on a medium heat.\r\n4.   Pour over the sauce (there will be some left).\r\n5.   Tear over pieces of Mozzarella.\r\n6.   Grate over some Parmesan.\r\n7.   Add other toppings to suit your taste. We added salami, fennel, a de-seeded chilli and black olives.\r\n8.   When the base is golden, place under the grill for 5 minutes to finish off the toppings.', '<ol>\n<li>For the base, mix 240g of flour with a little salt and small amounts of water until it binds.</li>\n<li>For the sauce, blend a tin of chopped tomatoes with a handful of basil, 2 garlic cloves, a lug of olive oil and a splash of balsamic.</li>\n<li>Roll the base and place it in a pan with a lug of oil on a medium heat.</li>\n<li>Pour over the sauce (there will be some left).</li>\n<li>Tear over pieces of Mozzarella.</li>\n<li>Grate over some Parmesan.</li>\n<li>Add other toppings to suit your taste. We added salami, fennel, a de-seeded chilli and black olives.</li>\n<li>When the base is golden, place under the grill for 5 minutes to finish off the toppings.</li>\n</ol>\n', '<p class="phil">This is a very good recipe for those in a rush, and you can impress your friends by making everything including the sauce and dough.</p>\r\n<p class="pete">Put the telephone down and step away from the takeaway menu! As soon as you try this recipe once you will never go back, I promise.</p>\r\n<p class="phil">We fry the dough off underneath to make it sturdy, ready to receive the toppings. We then finish it off under the grill to do the rest. Quick and easy, although not like a mamma used to make.</p>\r\n<p class="pete">The sauce can be quickly made using a blender. Once this and the dough are done, you can get the fun part, the toppings!</p>\r\n![pizza al forno with olives and feta](img/pizza-al-forno-good.jpg "pizza al forno with olives and feta")\r\n<p class="caption">We went a little crazy with this one. It has mozzarella, parmesan, salami, fennell, a red chilli, chestnut mushrooms, olives, and feta.</p>\r\n<p class="phil">You will be amazed with the taste. Although it is trying to be as authentic as possible, it isn''t trying too hard. Therefore it has its own unique flavour, which I think is much better than any takeaway could offer.</p>\r\n<p class="pete">And much cheaper. We are thinking of you.</p>\r\n![pizza al forno](img/pizza-al-forno.jpg "Pizza al forno")\r\n<p class="caption">You can have too many toppings. This is back to basics with just tomato, mozzarella and basil.</p>', '<p class="phil">This is a very good recipe for those in a rush, and you can impress your friends by making everything including the sauce and dough.</p>\n\n<p class="pete">Put the telephone down and step away from the takeaway menu! As soon as you try this recipe once you will never go back, I promise.</p>\n\n<p class="phil">We fry the dough off underneath to make it sturdy, ready to receive the toppings. We then finish it off under the grill to do the rest. Quick and easy, although not like a mamma used to make.</p>\n\n<p class="pete">The sauce can be quickly made using a blender. Once this and the dough are done, you can get the fun part, the toppings!</p>\n\n<img src="img/pizza-al-forno-good.jpg" alt="pizza al forno with olives and feta" title="pizza al forno with olives and feta" />\n\n<p class="caption">We went a little crazy with this one. It has mozzarella, parmesan, salami, fennell, a red chilli, chestnut mushrooms, olives, and feta.</p>\n\n<p class="phil">You will be amazed with the taste. Although it is trying to be as authentic as possible, it isn''t trying too hard. Therefore it has its own unique flavour, which I think is much better than any takeaway could offer.</p>\n\n<p class="pete">And much cheaper. We are thinking of you.</p>\n\n<img src="img/pizza-al-forno.jpg" alt="pizza al forno" title="Pizza al forno" />\n\n<p class="caption">You can have too many toppings. This is back to basics with just tomato, mozzarella and basil.</p>\n', '2015-05-05 20:31:28', 'pizza-al-forno'),
(12, 'Quesa-enchi-rrito', 'A homemade ensemble of Quesadillas, Enchiladas, and Burritos', 'Mexican beef tortillas', 'slices-of-quesadillas.jpg', '1.   Fry 500g of good quality steak mince with a couple of garlic cloves.\r\n2.   When browning add 2 sliced peppers, and a handful of chopped mushrooms.\r\n3.   Add 300ml of passata and mix.\r\n4.   Place 4 tortillas in the oven to warm up.\r\n5.   When ready, place the mix between the tortillas and sprinkle over some cheese, on the mix and on top of the tortillas.\r\n6.   Place back in the oven until the cheese melts.', '<ol>\n<li>Fry 500g of good quality steak mince with a couple of garlic cloves.</li>\n<li>When browning add 2 sliced peppers, and a handful of chopped mushrooms.</li>\n<li>Add 300ml of passata and mix.</li>\n<li>Place 4 tortillas in the oven to warm up.</li>\n<li>When ready, place the mix between the tortillas and sprinkle over some cheese, on the mix and on top of the tortillas.</li>\n<li>Place back in the oven until the cheese melts.</li>\n</ol>\n', '<p class="phil">We have no idea if this is a Quesadilla, Enchilada, or Burrito, but the taste is excellent.</p>\r\n<p class="pete">I hope we are not compounding our ignorance by saying that. Maybe someone can let us know in the comments!</p>\r\n<p class="phil">If you like more of a kick, add a chilli or three, we added some tabasco sauce in lieu of the chillis.</p>\r\n<p class="pete">People complain that Tabasco is merely there to add heat, not flavour, but I think once you get used to more heat in your food you can appreciate the flavour. It definitely added to the flavour and a nice lingering heat on the tongue, just to convince you that you are eating spicy Mexican food!</p>\r\n<p class="phil">Overall this is an extremely easy recipe. After you have experimented with your preferred combinations, you could easily smash this out in 15 minutes.</p>', '<p class="phil">We have no idea if this is a Quesadilla, Enchilada, or Burrito, but the taste is excellent.</p>\n\n<p class="pete">I hope we are not compounding our ignorance by saying that. Maybe someone can let us know in the comments!</p>\n\n<p class="phil">If you like more of a kick, add a chilli or three, we added some tabasco sauce in lieu of the chillis.</p>\n\n<p class="pete">People complain that Tabasco is merely there to add heat, not flavour, but I think once you get used to more heat in your food you can appreciate the flavour. It definitely added to the flavour and a nice lingering heat on the tongue, just to convince you that you are eating spicy Mexican food!</p>\n\n<p class="phil">Overall this is an extremely easy recipe. After you have experimented with your preferred combinations, you could easily smash this out in 15 minutes.</p>\n', '2015-05-09 13:25:33', 'quesa-enchi-rrito'),
(13, 'Spicy Chicken and zesty noodles', 'Five spice chicken with a fiery noodle dressing', 'chicken noodles five-spice', 'satay-chickay.jpg', '1.   Season chicken breasts with salt and pepper, and coat with five spice\r\n2.   Oil a pan and place chicken in over a medium heat\r\n3.   For the dressing, blend together half a red onion, a chilli, juice of 1 lime, 3-4 tbsp olive oil, 2 tbsp soy, 1 tsp sesame oil, 1 tsp fish sauce, and a bunch of coriander stalks\r\n4.   Warm a pan with a little oil ready for the nuts\r\n5.   Boil the kettle and get the noodles cooking\r\n6.   Add a pack of cashews to the hot pan. When brown, coat with honey and toss in some sesame seeds\r\n7.   When chicken is nearly cooked, coat with sweet chilli sauce and sesame seeds\r\n8.   Drain noodles and mix with the dressing and nuts. Add an optional chilli and coriander\r\n9.   Slice chicken and serve with noodles. Sprinkle coriander on top to serve', '<ol>\n<li>Season chicken breasts with salt and pepper, and coat with five spice</li>\n<li>Oil a pan and place chicken in over a medium heat</li>\n<li>For the dressing, blend together half a red onion, a chilli, juice of 1 lime, 3-4 tbsp olive oil, 2 tbsp soy, 1 tsp sesame oil, 1 tsp fish sauce, and a bunch of coriander stalks</li>\n<li>Warm a pan with a little oil ready for the nuts</li>\n<li>Boil the kettle and get the noodles cooking</li>\n<li>Add a pack of cashews to the hot pan. When brown, coat with honey and toss in some sesame seeds</li>\n<li>When chicken is nearly cooked, coat with sweet chilli sauce and sesame seeds</li>\n<li>Drain noodles and mix with the dressing and nuts. Add an optional chilli and coriander</li>\n<li>Slice chicken and serve with noodles. Sprinkle coriander on top to serve</li>\n</ol>\n', '<p class="pete">This is an extremely tasty recipe. It is a twist on a far eastern satay recipe, where instead of a peanut sauce, five spice is used to marinate the chicken. The zesty noodle dressing stays honest to its roots by providing the kick.</p>\r\n<p class="phil">Its got more kick than a mule whose just spotted a rotund beach goer approaching! Don''t be afraid to stray from the recipe to get the dressing just to your liking.</p>\r\n<p class="pete">Get the pan for the nuts nice and hot before adding them to get a nice browning to them.</p>\r\n<p class="phil">We used medium egg noodles. They provide a nice thick noodle to soak up the lovely dressing.</p>\r\n<p class="pete">The dressing is good for any dish. We may tackle the satay sauce next, which will also work with this dressing. It is very versatile.</p>\r\n![satay chicken](img/satay-chickay.jpg "satay chicken and noodles")\r\n<p class="caption">The final result</p>', '<p class="pete">This is an extremely tasty recipe. It is a twist on a far eastern satay recipe, where instead of a peanut sauce, five spice is used to marinate the chicken. The zesty noodle dressing stays honest to its roots by providing the kick.</p>\n\n<p class="phil">Its got more kick than a mule whose just spotted a rotund beach goer approaching! Don''t be afraid to stray from the recipe to get the dressing just to your liking.</p>\n\n<p class="pete">Get the pan for the nuts nice and hot before adding them to get a nice browning to them.</p>\n\n<p class="phil">We used medium egg noodles. They provide a nice thick noodle to soak up the lovely dressing.</p>\n\n<p class="pete">The dressing is good for any dish. We may tackle the satay sauce next, which will also work with this dressing. It is very versatile.</p>\n\n<img src="img/satay-chickay.jpg" alt="satay chicken" title="satay chicken and noodles" />\n\n<p class="caption">The final result</p>\n', '2015-05-16 15:55:34', 'spicy-chicken-and-zesty-noodles'),
(15, 'Pork Fennel Ragu', 'A heartwarming traditional pork and fennel pasta', 'Italian pork fennel pasta', 'pork-ragu.jpg', '1.   Blend 3/4 carrots, 2/3 spring onions, 1/2 sticks of celery and a red chilli\r\n2.   Add to a pan on a high heat\r\n3.   Blend 5 high quality pork sausages with a tsp of fennel seeds and a tsp of oregano\r\n4.   Add to pan and brown the meat\r\n5.   Add 3/4 crushed garlic cloves and 4 tbsp of balsamic vinegar\r\n6.  Add a tin of chopped tomatoes. Fill the tin with water and add to the pan\r\n7.   Boil the kettle and get the pasta cooking\r\n8.   When the ragu has reduced, add the cooked pasta and mix\r\n9.   Add a handful of chopped basil and sprinkle over Parmesan to serve', '<ol>\n<li>Blend 3/4 carrots, 2/3 spring onions, 1/2 sticks of celery and a red chilli</li>\n<li>Add to a pan on a high heat</li>\n<li>Blend 5 high quality pork sausages with a tsp of fennel seeds and a tsp of oregano</li>\n<li>Add to pan and brown the meat</li>\n<li>Add 3/4 crushed garlic cloves and 4 tbsp of balsamic vinegar</li>\n<li>Add a tin of chopped tomatoes. Fill the tin with water and add to the pan</li>\n<li>Boil the kettle and get the pasta cooking</li>\n<li>When the ragu has reduced, add the cooked pasta and mix</li>\n<li>Add a handful of chopped basil and sprinkle over Parmesan to serve</li>\n</ol>\n', '<p class="phil" markdown="1">We love this dish. It feels like authentic homemade Italian food and is sure to warm the cockles.</p>\r\n<p class="pete" markdown="1">Indeed. It is a useful recipe to use up veg, and can be a real fiery affair if you add more or stronger chillis. But do not attempt without a blender.</p>\r\n<p class="phil" markdown="1">I don''t even know how you''d tackle it without one, especially for the sausages.</p>\r\n<p class="pete" markdown="1">It is a dish that likes to motor along on a high heat, so don''t be afraid to turn the hob right up. Even when the sauce is bubbling along like [Grotbag''s](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grotbags "Grotbags-Wikipedia") cauldron, just put the lid on.</p>\r\n<p class="pete" markdown="1">Squashing the tomato chunks injects a jolt of flavour into the sauce, but don''t worry about getting them all, a juicy tomato chunk in the gob makes a nice surprise every now and again.</p>\r\n<p class="phil" markdown="1">Also, be sure to save some of the pasta water. There is a tendency for the pasta to dry up when you add it to the ragu, to the indignation of a million Italian nonnas. So add the water to the mix to prevent this from happening.</p>\r\n[![pork fennel pasta](img/1-pork-ragu.jpg "Pork and Fennel Pasta")](img/1-pork-ragu.jpg)\r\n<p class="caption" markdown="1">Ignore the tarts for now. We promise to write about these soon!</p>\r\n\r\n*[gob]: Mouth. Not pronounced jobe for all you Arrested Development fans.', '<p class="phil">We love this dish. It feels like authentic homemade Italian food and is sure to warm the cockles.</p>\n\n<p class="pete">Indeed. It is a useful recipe to use up veg, and can be a real fiery affair if you add more or stronger chillis. But do not attempt without a blender.</p>\n\n<p class="phil">I don''t even know how you''d tackle it without one, especially for the sausages.</p>\n\n<p class="pete">It is a dish that likes to motor along on a high heat, so don''t be afraid to turn the hob right up. Even when the sauce is bubbling along like <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grotbags" title="Grotbags-Wikipedia">Grotbag''s</a> cauldron, just put the lid on.</p>\n\n<p class="pete">Squashing the tomato chunks injects a jolt of flavour into the sauce, but don''t worry about getting them all, a juicy tomato chunk in the <abbr title="Mouth. Not pronounced jobe for all you Arrested Development fans.">gob</abbr> makes a nice surprise every now and again.</p>\n\n<p class="phil">Also, be sure to save some of the pasta water. There is a tendency for the pasta to dry up when you add it to the ragu, to the indignation of a million Italian nonnas. So add the water to the mix to prevent this from happening.</p>\n\n<a href="img/1-pork-ragu.jpg"><img src="img/1-pork-ragu.jpg" alt="pork fennel pasta" title="Pork and Fennel Pasta" /></a>\n\n<p class="caption">Ignore the tarts for now. We promise to write about these soon!</p>\n', '2015-05-17 11:51:43', 'pork-fennel-ragu'),
(16, 'Creamy Gnocchi', 'Lovely Italian dumplings in a creamy spinach sauce', 'Italian gnocchi creamy-sauce spinach', 'gnocchi-di-patate.jpg', '1.   Boil potatoes and drain well, allow them to cool.\r\n2.   Peel and rice.\r\n3.   Add flour, salt, and a beaten egg.\r\n4.   Form a dough.\r\n5.   Cut into slices, then chop the slices themselves into squares.\r\n6.   Cook in boiling water for 2-4 minutes.\r\n7.   For the sauce, heat oil in a pan and add garlic and tomatoes. Simmer.\r\n8.   Stir in mascarpone and cook for a couple of minutes.\r\n9.   Add spinach for the final minute of cooking the gnocchi.\r\n10.   Stir sauce through with gnocchi.', '<ol>\n<li>Boil potatoes and drain well, allow them to cool.</li>\n<li>Peel and rice.</li>\n<li>Add flour, salt, and a beaten egg.</li>\n<li>Form a dough.</li>\n<li>Cut into slices, then chop the slices themselves into squares.</li>\n<li>Cook in boiling water for 2-4 minutes.</li>\n<li>For the sauce, heat oil in a pan and add garlic and tomatoes. Simmer.</li>\n<li>Stir in mascarpone and cook for a couple of minutes.</li>\n<li>Add spinach for the final minute of cooking the gnocchi.</li>\n<li>Stir sauce through with gnocchi.</li>\n</ol>\n', 'A popular northern Italian dish this.\r\n\r\nMake sure to use good quality potatoes.\r\n\r\nFlour the gnocchi pieces when cut to stop them sticking. The first time we did this, we piled them in a bowl and ended up with a mutant single piece of giant gnocchi, not good.\r\n\r\nThe gnocchi will rise to the top of the pot when ready so just scoop them out with a slotted spoon.\r\n\r\n![gnocchi](img/gnocchiwithsauce.jpg "Gnocchi in a creamy spinach sauce")\r\n<p class="caption" markdown="1">Sprinkle over basil and parmesan to serve</p>', '<p>A popular northern Italian dish this.</p>\n\n<p>Make sure to use good quality potatoes.</p>\n\n<p>Flour the gnocchi pieces when cut to stop them sticking. The first time we did this, we piled them in a bowl and ended up with a mutant single piece of giant gnocchi, not good.</p>\n\n<p>The gnocchi will rise to the top of the pot when ready so just scoop them out with a slotted spoon.</p>\n\n<img src="img/gnocchiwithsauce.jpg" alt="gnocchi" title="Gnocchi in a creamy spinach sauce" />\n\n<p class="caption">Sprinkle over basil and parmesan to serve</p>\n', '2015-05-26 19:22:07', 'creamy-gnocchi'),
(17, 'Everybody Loves Ramen', 'Griddled chicken noodle soup', 'Japanese chicken soup', 'chicken-ramen.jpg', '1.   Get a griddle pan heating up (you want it hot!)\r\n2.   Season chicken breast with salt, pepper, and oil (we used groundnut oil for the high temperature)\r\n3.   Boil 350ml of water and add 2 scoops of chicken stock\r\n4.   Boil ramen noodles\r\n5.   Add noodles to a bowl, and pour over chicken stock\r\n6.   Slice the chicken and place on top of the noodles\r\n7.   Add a sliced pak choi, red chilli, coriander, spring onions, and a lime on top to serve', '<ol>\n<li>Get a griddle pan heating up (you want it hot!)</li>\n<li>Season chicken breast with salt, pepper, and oil (we used groundnut oil for the high temperature)</li>\n<li>Boil 350ml of water and add 2 scoops of chicken stock</li>\n<li>Boil ramen noodles</li>\n<li>Add noodles to a bowl, and pour over chicken stock</li>\n<li>Slice the chicken and place on top of the noodles</li>\n<li>Add a sliced pak choi, red chilli, coriander, spring onions, and a lime on top to serve</li>\n</ol>\n', 'Another Wagamama inspired recipe, this one is so quick and easy you''ll be amazed at the authentic flavour.\r\n\r\nRamen is a common Japanese noodle soup and is seen as the Japenese equivalent of fast food. Readers of the blog are probably aware that we have a penchant for street food of the world, and ramen fits neatly into this category.\r\n\r\nDon''t be restricted in terms of the additional ingredients you want to add. You could add leek, a boiled egg, beansprouts, menma (bamboo shoots, available in local Chinese/Japenese supermarkets), or nori (dried seaweed).\r\n\r\nYou can even experiment with the soup. For speed we just did a stock based soup using chicken stock powder, but ramen soup comes in many varieties. You can flavour it with soy, miso, mushrooms, or salt. We added chilli flakes to give it an extra kick.\r\n\r\nBeef or pork are also good replacements if you are out of chicken. But the noodles have to be specific, luckily ramen noodles are available in the major supermarkets.\r\n\r\n[![chilli chicken ramen](img/chicken-ramen.jpg "Everybody loves ra-men(d)")](img/chicken-ramen.jpg)\r\n<p class="caption" markdown="1">Please sir! Can I have some more?</p>\r\n\r\nThe taste is excellent for the effort involved. Serve with chopsticks for the noodles and a soup spoon for the broth. Try and get a good bite of all the ingredients for a smack of ultimate flavour.\r\n\r\nDon''t be afraid to slurp! This isn''t a dish for the polite consumer, hold the bowl up to your mouth for maximum slurpage and minimum sloppage.\r\n', '<p>Another Wagamama inspired recipe, this one is so quick and easy you''ll be amazed at the authentic flavour.</p>\n\n<p>Ramen is a common Japanese noodle soup and is seen as the Japenese equivalent of fast food. Readers of the blog are probably aware that we have a penchant for street food of the world, and ramen fits neatly into this category.</p>\n\n<p>Don''t be restricted in terms of the additional ingredients you want to add. You could add leek, a boiled egg, beansprouts, menma (bamboo shoots, available in local Chinese/Japenese supermarkets), or nori (dried seaweed).</p>\n\n<p>You can even experiment with the soup. For speed we just did a stock based soup using chicken stock powder, but ramen soup comes in many varieties. You can flavour it with soy, miso, mushrooms, or salt. We added chilli flakes to give it an extra kick.</p>\n\n<p>Beef or pork are also good replacements if you are out of chicken. But the noodles have to be specific, luckily ramen noodles are available in the major supermarkets.</p>\n\n<a href="img/chicken-ramen.jpg"><img src="img/chicken-ramen.jpg" alt="chilli chicken ramen" title="Everybody loves ra-men(d)" /></a>\n\n<p class="caption">Please sir! Can I have some more?</p>\n\n<p>The taste is excellent for the effort involved. Serve with chopsticks for the noodles and a soup spoon for the broth. Try and get a good bite of all the ingredients for a smack of ultimate flavour.</p>\n\n<p>Don''t be afraid to slurp! This isn''t a dish for the polite consumer, hold the bowl up to your mouth for maximum slurpage and minimum sloppage.</p>\n', '2015-07-05 12:19:55', 'everybody-loves-ramen'),
(18, 'Spaghetti alla Siciliana', 'Spaghetti in a sun dried tomato sauce', 'Italian spaghetti sun-dried-tomatoes', 'spaghetti-alla-siciliana.jpg', '1.   Cook spaghetti in a bowl of salted water\r\n2.   Add 2 tbsp of olive oil to a pan\r\n3.   Add 2 cloves of minced garlic\r\n4.   Add a handful of sliced sun-dried tomatoes\r\n5.   Add half of a bunch of sliced parsley\r\n6.   Sprinkle over 1-2 tsp of chilli flakes and stir together for 2 minutes\r\n7.   When spaghetti is ready, add to the tomatoes and mix together\r\n8.   Serve with the rest of sliced parsley and Parmesan', '<ol>\n<li>Cook spaghetti in a bowl of salted water</li>\n<li>Add 2 tbsp of olive oil to a pan</li>\n<li>Add 2 cloves of minced garlic</li>\n<li>Add a handful of sliced sun-dried tomatoes</li>\n<li>Add half of a bunch of sliced parsley</li>\n<li>Sprinkle over 1-2 tsp of chilli flakes and stir together for 2 minutes</li>\n<li>When spaghetti is ready, add to the tomatoes and mix together</li>\n<li>Serve with the rest of sliced parsley and Parmesan</li>\n</ol>\n', 'I count five ingredients at most in this. Plus if you take away the olive oil and garlic, which most respected cooks will already have in their kitchens, just leaves three ingredients that you need for this.\r\n\r\nIt is also so quick and easy to make. This recipe is courtesy of [Vikalinka](http://vikalinka.com/2013/11/06/spaghetti-alla-siciliana/ "Vikalinka-Spaghetti alla Siciliana"), and the simpleness of it inspired us to try it out. As mentioned, the quality of the resultant dish will depend heavily on the sun-dried tomatoes.\r\n\r\nUnfortunately we haven''t been able to get the real deal from Sicily, but the best we''ve found so far are from [Bella Sun Luci](http://bellasunluci.com/products.html "Bella Sun Luci products page") which are available from Costco.\r\n\r\n[![spaghetti alla siciliana](img/spaghetti-alla-siciliana.jpg "Spaghetti alla Siciliana")](img/spaghetti-alla-siciliana.jpg)\r\n<p class="caption" markdown="1">I love the contrasting colours.</p>\r\n\r\nThe sweetness of the tomatoes is contained by the garlic and the nutty/earthy taste of the parsley. Be sure to cook the spaghetti "al dente" (to the tooth, usually 8-10 mins) for a nice texture.', '<p>I count five ingredients at most in this. Plus if you take away the olive oil and garlic, which most respected cooks will already have in their kitchens, just leaves three ingredients that you need for this.</p>\n\n<p>It is also so quick and easy to make. This recipe is courtesy of <a href="http://vikalinka.com/2013/11/06/spaghetti-alla-siciliana/" title="Vikalinka-Spaghetti alla Siciliana">Vikalinka</a>, and the simpleness of it inspired us to try it out. As mentioned, the quality of the resultant dish will depend heavily on the sun-dried tomatoes.</p>\n\n<p>Unfortunately we haven''t been able to get the real deal from Sicily, but the best we''ve found so far are from <a href="http://bellasunluci.com/products.html" title="Bella Sun Luci products page">Bella Sun Luci</a> which are available from Costco.</p>\n\n<a href="img/spaghetti-alla-siciliana.jpg"><img src="img/spaghetti-alla-siciliana.jpg" alt="spaghetti alla siciliana" title="Spaghetti alla Siciliana" /></a>\n\n<p class="caption">I love the contrasting colours.</p>\n\n<p>The sweetness of the tomatoes is contained by the garlic and the nutty/earthy taste of the parsley. Be sure to cook the spaghetti "al dente" (to the tooth, usually 8-10 mins) for a nice texture.</p>\n', '2015-07-05 12:49:39', 'spaghetti-alla-siciliana');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`, `title`, `summary`, `tags`, `banner_image_path`, `directions_md`, `directions_html`, `content_md`, `content_html`, `pubDate`, `url`) VALUES
(19, 'This Is A Tasty Burger', 'A burger with a twist of fiery sun-dried tomato paste. Vegetarians need not apply.', 'beef burger sun-dried-tomato', 'sun-dried-tomato-paste-burger-banner.JPG', '1.  Season some good quality, high fat steak mince, add a small HF of chopped parsley and knead together.\r\n2.  For the paste, blend a HF of sun-dried tomatoes, HF of chillies, several cloves of garlic, soy sauce for consistency, and a splash of olive oil.\r\n3.  Form mince into 2 thin patties (for a single burger), and add a tsp of paste in the centre of the bottom patty. Place the 2nd patty on top and pinch around the edge to seal the burger.\r\n4.  Oven cook on a grill to let the grease escape.\r\n5.  When cooked turn off the oven, place cheese on top of the burgers and return to the oven to melt the cheese.\r\n6.  Cut a brioche bun and garnish to your taste (see main article), and add the burgers to finish.', '<ol>\n<li>Season some good quality, high fat steak mince, add a small HF of chopped parsley and knead together.</li>\n<li>For the paste, blend a HF of sun-dried tomatoes, HF of chillies, several cloves of garlic, soy sauce for consistency, and a splash of olive oil.</li>\n<li>Form mince into 2 thin patties (for a single burger), and add a tsp of paste in the centre of the bottom patty. Place the 2nd patty on top and pinch around the edge to seal the burger.</li>\n<li>Oven cook on a grill to let the grease escape.</li>\n<li>When cooked turn off the oven, place cheese on top of the burgers and return to the oven to melt the cheese.</li>\n<li>Cut a brioche bun and garnish to your taste (see main article), and add the burgers to finish.</li>\n</ol>\n', '*[meathooks]: hands\r\n*[trough]: feast in an animal-like fashion using hands to fill the mouth with feverish abandon\r\n*[laughing tackle]: mouth\r\n\r\n<p class="phil" markdown="1">As with all truly great adventures, this one begins, with a burgerâ€¦</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="pete" markdown="1">Unlike poor Samuel L. Jackson in Pulp Fiction, [we do not have vegetarians to cater for](https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dBP0Mbc7VFw "Pulp Fiction Hamburger scene"). So the ideal first recipe of this blog is a meat lover''s paradise, a succulent, juicy burger with a fiery secret that you won''t be able to keep to yourself.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="phil" markdown="1">This burger is a beautiful thing. It should (if you have a soul) strike chords on your taste buds that other burgers just can''t strum! From the moment you get your laughing tackle round the sweet tasting brioche, to the moment your teeth sink into the hot pocket of flavour and it bursts with tomato and spice it''s just ace. Satisfaction follows every bite and i couldn''t help but grin gormlessly for a few seconds after Iâ€™d finished it, only coming back to Earth when I realised there was nothing more to enjoy.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="pete" markdown="1">We''re certain you''re going to love this one. It''s a classic surprise dish. Your guests will be looking at a nice but simple looking burger, but something unexpected lurks inside. A flavour within a flavour. BANG! The spicy hit of the tomato paste will leave them in no doubt of your culinary prowess. This is why I wanted to call it an inception burger, but I was vetoed on the minor technicality that it is not a dream within a dream, or even a burger within a burger.</p>\r\n\r\n[![sun dried tomato paste burger](img/tasty-burger.JPG "the final ensemble")](img/tasty-burger.JPG)\r\n<p class="caption" markdown="1">The final ensemble.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="phil" markdown="1">Burgers within burgers is the obvious next evolutionary step, but weâ€™re not there yet. Right now people still don''t understand current burger technology and rely on shops to produce them. Burgers should never be shop bought. Philistines who commit this heinous crime cite time and expense as excuses. All of this is lies. These burgers from mince to cooked patty took about 40 minutes and cost little more than decent shop bought alternatives. Take my word on it, the ends more than justify the means.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="pete" markdown="1">The paste is immense. It will taste very hot initially, especially if you leave the chilli seeds in. But trust us, this will die down once cooked inside the burger. The individual patties should be made as thin as possible because a) you need two to get the paste in the middle, 2) they swell when cooked, and d) it will allow a bigger area for garnish, as opposed to a shrunken ball of beef. Any leftover paste can be used as a sauce in the burger, but on the underside of the crown please, there are rules!</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="pull-quote"><i class="fa fa-quote-left fa-2x fa-pull-left"></i>You wouldn''t build your house upside down and expect anything less than a bad time when you tried to eat it. It''s the same with burgers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="pete" markdown="1">If you like more sauce in your burger you can add mayo or whatever to the heel. Whatever is on the heel will hit the tongue first so too much heat will numb the tongue before the onslaught of flavour. NEVER put hot sauce on the heel for this reason. </p>\r\n\r\n#### Phil''s 4 laws of burger construction\r\n<p class="phil" markdown="1">Burger law! Follow a few simple laws, and youâ€™ll be a burger fiend and homemade convert in no time! Laws? Regarding burger construction?..... well yes, you wouldn''t build your house upside down and expect anything less than a bad time when you tried to eat it. It''s the same with burgers. Here''s a set of laws to help keep you from ruining your masterpiece.</p>\r\n\r\n[![An exploded view of the law of burger assembly](assets/phils-law-of-burger-assembly.jpg "An exploded view of the law of burger assembly")](assets/phils-law-of-burger-assembly.jpg)\r\n<p class="caption" markdown="1">This law is immutable.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="phil" markdown="1">1.  The heel. The heel of the burger serves a single vital purpose, it supports the burger and stops your meathooks getting covered in grease. Sauce may be applied but not hot sauce.... you''re not a monster.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="phil" markdown="1">2.  The patty. Only one option here, one patty if you''re a gentleman, or two if you''re a man.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="phil" markdown="1">3.  The garnish. A compendium of joy and flavour that can set your burger apart. Even a rat meat, low fat, chicken foot patty can be made awesome if this stage is done right.<br>\r\na.  Onions first, or anything thatâ€™ll fit flat against the burger, unlike that Judas piece of iceberg lettuce. Lay the foundations right from the start and your burger won''t come apart. One cool trick is to use the hollow in the centre of the onion (fried-ring or otherwise) to hold some chopped chillies or tomato chutney - Youâ€™re Welcome!<br>\r\nb.  Sliced mushrooms? Perhaps some bacon? Go nuts! Put whatever else you want here, even hot sauce if you''re feeling naughty.<br>\r\nc.  The aforementioned Judas piece of flattering-to-deceive lettuce. All it adds is an aesthetic piece of greenery to make the rest of the garnish look even more enticing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="phil" markdown="1">4.  The Crown. The piÃ¨ce de rÃ©sistance, the final piece of the puzzle. This is also a good place to put your hot sauce. You''ll still get a huge kick from it, but it gives the rest of the burger time to impress you also. This is particularly important, if, like me, you appreciate the beauty of a habanero and scotch bonnet tour de force.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="pete" markdown="1">Final garnish is entirely your choice. But we found that the cheese is an important binding agent to prevent the burger topping spilling out of the sides. The cheaper the better. The processed, vibrant orange variety seems to work really well as you get a good melt on top of the burger.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="phil" markdown="1">Cheap American style burger cheese! If it''s a cheeseburger, that''s the key. It forms an awesome orange vacuum packed seal that posh cheeses don''t seem to provide. It glues the burger together and makes it easier to trough on!</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="pete" markdown="1">To top it off we recommend a brioche bun. The whole ensemble can be ruined by a bad bun choice. The brioche bun just looks right, and the slightly richer flavour adds to the overall power.</p>\r\n\r\n<p class="phil" markdown="1">All good meals present the culinary ponderer with a new life lesson. The lesson from this is, don''t cut corners, get stuck in and you''ll enjoy the fruits of your labour!</p>\r\n\r\n![Christian Bale is pleased](img/bale.gif "Christian Bale concurs")\r\n<p class="caption" markdown="1">Christian Bale concurs. Do you? Let us know by dropping us a comment.</p>', '<p class="phil">As with all truly great adventures, this one begins, with a burgerâ€¦</p>\n\n<p class="pete">Unlike poor Samuel L. Jackson in Pulp Fiction, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=dBP0Mbc7VFw" title="Pulp Fiction Hamburger scene">we do not have vegetarians to cater for</a>. So the ideal first recipe of this blog is a meat lover''s paradise, a succulent, juicy burger with a fiery secret that you won''t be able to keep to yourself.</p>\n\n<p class="phil">This burger is a beautiful thing. It should (if you have a soul) strike chords on your taste buds that other burgers just can''t strum! From the moment you get your <abbr title="mouth">laughing tackle</abbr> round the sweet tasting brioche, to the moment your teeth sink into the hot pocket of flavour and it bursts with tomato and spice it''s just ace. Satisfaction follows every bite and i couldn''t help but grin gormlessly for a few seconds after Iâ€™d finished it, only coming back to Earth when I realised there was nothing more to enjoy.</p>\n\n<p class="pete">We''re certain you''re going to love this one. It''s a classic surprise dish. Your guests will be looking at a nice but simple looking burger, but something unexpected lurks inside. A flavour within a flavour. BANG! The spicy hit of the tomato paste will leave them in no doubt of your culinary prowess. This is why I wanted to call it an inception burger, but I was vetoed on the minor technicality that it is not a dream within a dream, or even a burger within a burger.</p>\n\n<a href="img/tasty-burger.JPG"><img src="img/tasty-burger.JPG" alt="sun dried tomato paste burger" title="the final ensemble" /></a>\n\n<p class="caption">The final ensemble.</p>\n\n<p class="phil">Burgers within burgers is the obvious next evolutionary step, but weâ€™re not there yet. Right now people still don''t understand current burger technology and rely on shops to produce them. Burgers should never be shop bought. Philistines who commit this heinous crime cite time and expense as excuses. All of this is lies. These burgers from mince to cooked patty took about 40 minutes and cost little more than decent shop bought alternatives. Take my word on it, the ends more than justify the means.</p>\n\n<p class="pete">The paste is immense. It will taste very hot initially, especially if you leave the chilli seeds in. But trust us, this will die down once cooked inside the burger. The individual patties should be made as thin as possible because a) you need two to get the paste in the middle, 2) they swell when cooked, and d) it will allow a bigger area for garnish, as opposed to a shrunken ball of beef. Any leftover paste can be used as a sauce in the burger, but on the underside of the crown please, there are rules!</p>\n\n<p class="pull-quote"><i class="fa fa-quote-left fa-2x fa-pull-left"></i>You wouldn''t build your house upside down and expect anything less than a bad time when you tried to eat it. It''s the same with burgers.</p>\n\n<p class="pete">If you like more sauce in your burger you can add mayo or whatever to the heel. Whatever is on the heel will hit the tongue first so too much heat will numb the tongue before the onslaught of flavour. NEVER put hot sauce on the heel for this reason. </p>\n\n<h4>Phil''s 4 laws of burger construction</h4>\n\n<p class="phil">Burger law! Follow a few simple laws, and youâ€™ll be a burger fiend and homemade convert in no time! Laws? Regarding burger construction?..... well yes, you wouldn''t build your house upside down and expect anything less than a bad time when you tried to eat it. It''s the same with burgers. Here''s a set of laws to help keep you from ruining your masterpiece.</p>\n\n<a href="assets/phils-law-of-burger-assembly.jpg"><img src="assets/phils-law-of-burger-assembly.jpg" alt="An exploded view of the law of burger assembly" title="An exploded view of the law of burger assembly" /></a>\n\n<p class="caption">This law is immutable.</p>\n\n<p class="phil">1.  The heel. The heel of the burger serves a single vital purpose, it supports the burger and stops your <abbr title="hands">meathooks</abbr> getting covered in grease. Sauce may be applied but not hot sauce.... you''re not a monster.</p>\n\n<p class="phil">2.  The patty. Only one option here, one patty if you''re a gentleman, or two if you''re a man.</p>\n\n<p class="phil">3.  The garnish. A compendium of joy and flavour that can set your burger apart. Even a rat meat, low fat, chicken foot patty can be made awesome if this stage is done right.<br>\na.  Onions first, or anything thatâ€™ll fit flat against the burger, unlike that Judas piece of iceberg lettuce. Lay the foundations right from the start and your burger won''t come apart. One cool trick is to use the hollow in the centre of the onion (fried-ring or otherwise) to hold some chopped chillies or tomato chutney - Youâ€™re Welcome!<br>\nb.  Sliced mushrooms? Perhaps some bacon? Go nuts! Put whatever else you want here, even hot sauce if you''re feeling naughty.<br>\nc.  The aforementioned Judas piece of flattering-to-deceive lettuce. All it adds is an aesthetic piece of greenery to make the rest of the garnish look even more enticing.</p>\n\n<p class="phil">4.  The Crown. The piÃ¨ce de rÃ©sistance, the final piece of the puzzle. This is also a good place to put your hot sauce. You''ll still get a huge kick from it, but it gives the rest of the burger time to impress you also. This is particularly important, if, like me, you appreciate the beauty of a habanero and scotch bonnet tour de force.</p>\n\n<p class="pete">Final garnish is entirely your choice. But we found that the cheese is an important binding agent to prevent the burger topping spilling out of the sides. The cheaper the better. The processed, vibrant orange variety seems to work really well as you get a good melt on top of the burger.</p>\n\n<p class="phil">Cheap American style burger cheese! If it''s a cheeseburger, that''s the key. It forms an awesome orange vacuum packed seal that posh cheeses don''t seem to provide. It glues the burger together and makes it easier to <abbr title="feast in an animal-like fashion using hands to fill the mouth with feverish abandon">trough</abbr> on!</p>\n\n<p class="pete">To top it off we recommend a brioche bun. The whole ensemble can be ruined by a bad bun choice. The brioche bun just looks right, and the slightly richer flavour adds to the overall power.</p>\n\n<p class="phil">All good meals present the culinary ponderer with a new life lesson. The lesson from this is, don''t cut corners, get stuck in and you''ll enjoy the fruits of your labour!</p>\n\n<img src="img/bale.gif" alt="Christian Bale is pleased" title="Christian Bale concurs" />\n\n<p class="caption">Christian Bale concurs. Do you? Let us know by dropping us a comment.</p>\n', '2015-08-01 17:25:13', 'this-is-a-tasty-burger');

